---
import { CONTACT_LINKS } from "../config/site";
import SystemPageLayout from "../layouts/SystemPageLayout.astro";
---

<SystemPageLayout
  title="About"
  moduleCode="OPERATOR-RECORD"
  description="Background, interests, and the route that led me toward systems engineering."
  counter="4 SECTIONS"
>
  <div class="operator-record">
    <aside class="operator-panel" aria-label="Operator summary">
      <div class="operator-avatar" aria-hidden="true">
        <span>TD</span>
      </div>

      <div class="operator-identity">
        <p>OPERATOR RECORD</p>
        <h2>TIEN DU</h2>
      </div>

      <dl>
        <div>
          <dt>BASE</dt>
          <dd>Vietnam</dd>
        </div>
        <div>
          <dt>DOMAIN</dt>
          <dd>Platform operations</dd>
        </div>
        <div>
          <dt>SYSTEMS</dt>
          <dd>Linux / Cloud / Distributed workloads</dd>
        </div>
        <div>
          <dt>FOCUS</dt>
          <dd>Reliability / Automation / Tooling</dd>
        </div>
      </dl>

      <nav class="operator-links" aria-label="Profile and contact links">
        {
          CONTACT_LINKS.map(({ href, label, external }) => (
            <a
              href={href}
              target={external ? "_blank" : undefined}
              rel={external ? "noopener noreferrer" : undefined}
            >
              {label}
            </a>
          ))
        }
      </nav>
    </aside>

    <div class="about-copy">
      <section aria-labelledby="profile-heading">
        <p class="system-section-code">01 / PROFILE</p>
        <h2 id="profile-heading">A little about me</h2>
        <p class="about-lead">
          I'm a platform operations engineer based in Vietnam. I'm interested in
          dependable systems, useful tools, and understanding why things fail.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section aria-labelledby="route-heading">
        <p class="system-section-code">02 / ROUTE</p>
        <h2 id="route-heading">How I got here</h2>

        <p>
          My background is in biotechnology and bioinformatics rather than
          traditional computer science. I completed a BSc in Biotechnology in
          Singapore in 2017, followed by an MSc in Bioinformatics and
          Computational Biology in Ireland in 2019.
        </p>

        <p>
          I later entered a PhD programme, but left in 2023 after deciding it was
          no longer the right path for me. It was a difficult and sad decision,
          but also a deliberate one. It gave me space to reconsider the kind of
          work I actually wanted to do.
        </p>

        <div class="timeline" aria-label="Education and career timeline">
          <div class="timeline-row">
            <span>2017</span>
            <p>BSc in Biotechnology, completed in Singapore.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="timeline-row">
            <span>2019</span>
            <p>MSc in Bioinformatics and Computational Biology in Ireland.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="timeline-row">
            <span>2023</span>
            <p>Left academia and moved more deliberately toward engineering.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="timeline-row">
            <span>NOW</span>
            <p>Platform operations, reliability, automation, and technical writing.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section aria-labelledby="work-heading">
        <p class="system-section-code">03 / SYSTEMS</p>
        <h2 id="work-heading">The work underneath the science</h2>

        <p>
          I started in scientific research, working with biological data and
          computational workflows. Over time, I became increasingly interested in
          the engineering underneath them:
        </p>

        <ul class="question-list">
          <li><span aria-hidden="true">&gt;</span> Why did this job fail after running for two days?</li>
          <li><span aria-hidden="true">&gt;</span> Why can nobody reproduce this environment?</li>
          <li><span aria-hidden="true">&gt;</span> Where did the storage disappear?</li>
          <li><span aria-hidden="true">&gt;</span> Why is this process still retrying after a month?</li>
          <li><span aria-hidden="true">&gt;</span> How do we make the system easier to operate next time?</li>
        </ul>

        <p>
          That gradually pulled me toward Linux systems, cloud infrastructure,
          distributed workloads, automation, observability, and reliability
          engineering.
        </p>

        <p>
          Today, I investigate production failures, build operational tooling,
          improve cloud usage, document failure modes, and help make complicated
          systems less fragile. I do not think reliability means that nothing ever
          fails. It means failures are visible, understandable, recoverable, and
          less likely to surprise the next person.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section aria-labelledby="outside-heading">
        <p class="system-section-code">04 / OUTSIDE WORK</p>
        <h2 id="outside-heading">Outside work</h2>

        <p>
          I like coffee, photography, and simple things that reward attention.
          I especially like sunlight passing through leaves—the Japanese word
          {" "}<em>komorebi</em>{" "}
          describes it better than I can.
        </p>

        <p>
          I also have a soft spot for mechanical things: watches, cars, tools, and
          machines whose behaviour can be observed and understood. Perhaps that is
          part of why systems engineering appeals to me. I like things that are
          dependable, maintainable, and honest about how they work.
        </p>
      </section>
    </div>
  </div>
</SystemPageLayout>
